%N A197594 Sum of the cubes of the first odd numbers up to a(n) equals the n-th perfect number.
%C A197594 Except for the first perfect number 6, every even perfect number 2^(p-1)*(2^p - 1) is the sum of the cubes of the first 2^((p-1)/2) odd numbers.
%D A197594 Albert H. Beiler: Recreations in the theory of numbers, New York, Dover, Second Edition, 1966, p. 22.
%F A197594 1/8*(a(n) + 1)^2*(a(n)^2 + 2*a(n) - 1) = 2^(p-1)*(2^p - 1) with p = 2*log(a(n) + 1)/log(2) - 1 a Mersenne prime.
%F A197594 a(n) = 2^((A000043(n)+1)/2) - 1. [_Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 17 2011]
%F A197594 a(n) = sqrt(1 + sqrt(8*A000396(n) + 1)) - 1. [_Martin Renner_, Oct 17 2011]
